Name: Apples
Description: The apple is native to Central Asia and have been grown for thousands of years in Asia and Europe. There are more than 7,500 known varieties of apples. Varieties bred for raw consumption are termed dessert or table apples, those for cooking or cider production are known as cooking apples. Cider apples are typically too tart and astringent to eat fresh. Apples have a moderate content of dietary fiber but otherwise generally have a low content of essential nutrients.

Name: Apricots
Description: Apricots are a stone fruit in the same family as plums, cherries, peaches and almonds. The flesh of the apricot is usually firm and not very juicy and its taste can range from sweet to tart. Raw apricots are a moderate source of vitamin A and vitamin C. When apricots are dried, the relative concentration of nutrients is increased, and they become a rich source of  vitamin A, vitamin E, potassium and iron.

Name: Artichokes
Description: The artichoke is a variety thistle cultivated as a food and is native to the Mediterranean area. The edible portion of the plant consists of the flower buds before the flowers come into bloom. Artichokes are boiled or steamed and a cooked, unseasoned artichoke has a delicate flavour.  Artichokes are a rich source of folate and sodium and a good source of vitamin K, magnesium, manganese and phosphorus.

Name: Arugula
Description: Arugula is also called rocket salad, rucola, rucoli, rugula, colewort, and roquette. Arugula is widely popular as a salad vegetable, and is native to the Mediterranean region; from Morocco and Portugal in the west to Syria, Lebanon, and Turkey in the east. It is a pungent, leafy green vegetable resembling a longer-leaved and open lettuce and the leaves, flowers, young seed pods and mature seeds are all edible. It is a rich source of vitamin A and vitamin C and a good source of calcium.

Name: Asian Pears
Description: Asian pears represent several species of pear trees native to East Asia. The tree's edible fruit is known by many names, including: Asian pear, Chinese pear, Korean pear, Japanese pear, Taiwanese pear, sand pear, and nashi pear. The fruit are large and fragrant and are commonly served raw and peeled. They are generally not baked in pies or made into jams because they have a high water content and a crisp, grainy texture which is unsuitable for these uses. They have low overall nutritional content.

Name: Asparagus
Description: Asparagus is also known as garden asparagus and sparrow grass. It has been consumed since antiquity and a recipe for cooking asparagus is found in the oldest surviving book of recipes dated from the 3rd century AD. Only young asparagus shoots are commonly eaten as once the buds start to open, the shoots quickly turn woody.  Asparagus is low in calories, is very low in sodium, is a rich source of dietary fiber and vitamin K, and a good source of thiamine, riboflavin, folate and iron.

Name: Avocados
Description: The avocado is a tree in the laurel family thought to have originated in South Central Mexico. Avocado also refers to the tree's fruit, which is botanically a berry and contains a single large seed. The fruit has a markedly higher fat content than most other fruit, mostly monounsaturated fat, and is used in both savory and sweet dishes, usually being served raw.  Avocados are moderate to rich in several B vitamins and vitamin K, with good content of vitamin C, vitamin E and potassium.

Name: Bananas
Description: The banana plant is the largest of the herbaceous flowering plants, often mistaken for a tree, and the banana fruit is botanically a berry. Bananas used for cooking may be called plantains, in contrast to dessert bananas which are eaten raw. They are a rich source of vitamin B6, and contain moderate amounts of vitamin C, manganese and dietary fiber. Contrary to popular belief, bananas are not a good source of potassium.

Name: Basil
Description: Basil, also called great basil or Saint-Joseph's-wort, is a culinary herb in the mint family. It is native to tropical regions from central Africa and Southeast Asia. Basil is used in cuisines worldwide, the leaves taste somewhat like anise, with a strong, pungent, often sweet smell. It is most commonly used fresh in recipes and is generally added at the last moment, as cooking quickly destroys the flavor.  Basil is an excellent source of vitamin K, and a rich source of vitamin A, vitamin C, calcium, copper, iron, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Beets
Description: The beetroot, also known as the beet, table beet, garden beet, red beet, or golden beet, is the taproot portion of the beet plant. The roots of beetroot are eaten boiled, roasted or raw, either alone or combined with salad, and are often pickled. Raw beetroot is a rich source of folate and a moderate source of manganese, with other nutrients having insignificant content.

Name: Black Eyed Peas
Description: The black-eyed pea, also known as black-eyed bean or goat pea, is a legume and is a subspecies of the cowpea, grown around the world for its medium-sized, edible bean. The common commercial variety is called the California Blackeye; it is pale-colored with a prominent black spot. The color of the eye may be black, brown, red, pink or green.  They are an excellent source of folate, and a rich source of thiamine, iron, manganese and phosphorus, and a good source of magnesium and zinc.

Name: Blackberries
Description: Blackberries are the edible fruit from several species of plants in the rose family. The soft fruit is popular for use in desserts, jams, seedless jelly, and sometimes wine. Cultivated blackberries offer a rich source of dietary fiber, vitamin C, vitamin K, but other essential nutrients are low in content. They contain both soluble and insoluble fiber components.

Name: Blueberries
Description: Blueberries are perennial flowering plants with indigo-colored berries, and are related to cranberries, bilberries and grouseberries. They are sold fresh, frozen or processed as fruit pur√©e, juice, or dried or infused berries. They can be eaten raw and used in jellies, jams, and baked goods. They contain only negligible amounts of micronutrients, offering moderate levels of manganese, vitamin C, vitamin K and dietary fiber.

Name: Bok Choy
Description: Bok choy, also known as pak choi or pok choi, is a type of Chinese cabbage. Chinese cabbage varieties are popular in southern China and Southeast Asia, but being winter-hardy, they are increasingly grown in Northern Europe. It is a rich source of vitamin A, vitamin C and vitamin K, and a good source of folate, vitamin B6, and calcium.

Name: Boysenberries
Description: The boysenberry is a cross among the European raspberry, European blackberry, American dewberry, and loganberry. Boysenberries are characterized by their soft texture, thin skins, and sweet-tart flavor. Mature fruits leak juice very easily and can start to decay within a few days of harvest. Boysenberries are a rich source of vitamin C and dietary fiber but are low in other essential nutrients.

Name: Brambles
Description: In British English, a bramble is any rough tangled prickly shrub, but specifically refers to the blackberry bush. Bramble or brambleberry may also refer to the blackberry fruit or products of its fruit, for example bramble jelly.

Name: Broccoli
Description: Broccoli is an edible green plant in the cabbage family whose large flowering head is eaten as a vegetable. It is often boiled, steamed or eaten raw. Broccoli is the result of careful selective cultivation in the Mediterranean region dating back to the 6th century. Broccoli is an excellent source of vitamin C and vitamin K, and raw broccoli contains moderate amounts of several B vitamins and manganese, but offers few other essential nutrients.

Name: Brussels Sprouts
Description: The brussels sprout is a member of the cabbage family and is grown for its edible buds. These can be cooked by boiling, steaming, stir frying, grilling, slow cooking, or roasting. Overcooking will render the buds gray and soft, and they then develop a strong flavor and odor that some dislike. Raw Brussels sprouts contain excellent levels of vitamin C and vitamin K, with more moderate amounts of folate and vitamin B6.

Name: Burdock
Description: The taproot of young burdock plants can be harvested and eaten as a root vegetable. Native to Europe and Asia, several species have been widely introduced worldwide. Burdock root is very crisp and has a sweet, mild, pungent flavor with a little muddy harshness that can be reduced by soaking julienned or shredded roots in water for five or ten minutes. Burdock seeds or burrs are covered in small hooks and were the inspiration for Velcro.

Name: Cabbage
Description: Cabbage or headed cabbage is a leafy green, red, or white biennial plant grown as an annual vegetable crop for its dense-leaved heads. It was most likely domesticated somewhere in Europe before 1000 BC. Cabbage is a rich source of vitamin C and vitamin K, and is also a moderate source of vitamin B6 and folate, with no other nutrients having significant content.

Name: Cantaloupe
Description: The cantaloupe is also known as muskmelon, mushmelon, rockmelon, sweet melon, and spanspek. The cantaloupe most likely originated in a region from India to Africa. It is normally eaten as a fresh fruit, as a salad, or as a dessert. Because the surface of a cantaloupe can contain harmful bacteria it is recommended to wash and scrub a melon thoroughly before cutting and consumption. Fresh cantaloupe is a rich source of vitamin C and vitamin A, with other nutrients in negligible amounts.

Name: Cardoons
Description: The cardoon is also called the artichoke thistle or globe artichoke, is part of the sunflower family. It is native to the western and central Mediterranean region, where it was domesticated in ancient times. While the flower buds can be eaten as small artichokes, more often the stems are eaten after being braised in cooking liquid. They have an artichoke-like flavor with a hint of bitterness. They are a good source of folate, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Carrots
Description: The carrot is a biennial plant in the same family at celery and parsley. Carrots are a domesticated form of the wild carrot, native to Central Asia, probably Persia. Only 3 percent of the beta-carotene in raw carrots is released during digestion but this can be improved to 39% by pulping, cooking and adding cooking oil. The greens are edible as a leaf vegetable, but are rarely eaten by humans. Carrots are a rich source of vitamin A, and are also a good source of vitamin K and vitamin B6, but otherwise have modest content of other essential nutrients.

Name: Cauliflower
Description: Cauliflower is an annual plant of the cabbage family. Typically, only the head is eaten, and the edible white flesh is sometimes called curd. Cauliflower heads can be roasted, boiled, fried, steamed, pickled, or eaten raw. The outer leaves are edible but are usually discarded. Cauliflower is rich in vitamin C and a good source of vitamin B5, vitamin B6, folate and vitamin K.

Name: Celery
Description: Celery is a marshland plant that has been cultivated as a vegetable since antiquity. It is thought to be native to the Mediterranean region. The leaf stalks and stems are usually eaten, the strongly flavored leaves are used as a flavoring or as a dried herb.  Celery is a rich source of vitamin K but offers very little by way of other nutrients.

Name: Celery Root
Description: Celery root is also called turnip-rooted celery, or knob celery. It is a variety of celery cultivated for its edible roots, stem, and shoots, and originated in the Mediterranean Basin. It is edible raw or cooked, and tastes similar to the stalks of common celery. It may be roasted, stewed, blanched, or mashed. It is a rich source of vitamin K and a good source of vitamin B6, vitamin C and phosphorus.

Name: Chard
Description: Chard is also known as Swiss chard, silver beet, perpetual spinach, beet spinach, seakale beet, or leaf beet. It is a green leafy vegetable native to the Mediterranean. Fresh young chard can be used raw in salads, and mature chard leaves and stalks are typically cooked. The natural bitterness fades with cooking, leaving a refined flavour which is more delicate than that of cooked spinach. Chard is rich source of vitamins A, K, and C, and a good source of vitamin E, magnesium, manganese, iron and potassium.

Name: Cherries
Description: The indigenous range of the sweet cherry extends through most of Europe, western Asia, and parts of northern Africa. Cultivated cherries are either sweet cherries for eating or sour cherries for cooking. Raw sweet cherries provide little nutrient content, having only moderate amounts of dietary fiber and vitamin C, and almost no other micronutrients. Raw sour cherries contain slightly higher vitamin C and vitamin A.

Name: Chestnuts
Description: The chestnut is a group of eight or nine species of deciduous trees and shrubs in the beech family native to temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere. The fruit of the chestnut tree, known simply as chestnuts, are unusual for nuts in that they have very little protein, their calories coming chiefly from carbohydrates. They also contain very little fat, mostly unsaturated, and no gluten. Unlike other nuts they contain vitamin C. They are a good source of thiamine, vitamin B6, folate and potassium.

Name: Chickpeas
Description: The chickpea is a legume and its different types are also known as gram, Bengal gram, garbanzo, garbanzo bean, or Egyptian pea. It is one of the earliest cultivated legumes, and 7,500-year-old remains have been found in the Middle East. They are a nutrient-dense food, providing rich content of protein, dietary fibre, folate, iron, and phosphorus, and are a good source of thiamin, vitamin B6, magnesium, and zinc.

Name: Chicories
Description: Common, also known as blue daisy, coffeeweed, horseweed, succory and wild endive, is a perennial herbaceous plant of the dandelion family native to Europe. Many varieties are cultivated for salad leaves which usually have a bitter taste. The roots can be baked and ground, and used as a coffee substitute and additive. Chicory is a rich source of vitamin A, vitamin B5, folate, vitamin C and especially vitamin K.  It is also a good source of calcium and manganese.

Name: Chili Peppers
Description: The chili pepper, also chile pepper, chilli pepper, or simply chilli, is the fruit of plants that are members of the nightshade family. Chili peppers originated in Mexico. They are widely used in many cuisines to add spiciness to dishes. The substances that give chili peppers their hotness are capsaicin and related compounds known as capsaicinoids. Red chilies contain large amounts of vitamin C, and other species contain significant amounts of provitamin A beta-carotene. In addition, chili peppers are a rich source of vitamin B6.

Name: Chives
Description: Chives are in the same family as onion, garlic, scallion and leek. They are used as a flavoring herb, and provide a somewhat milder flavor than those of other members of the family. They are native to temperate areas of Europe, Asia and North America. The scapes, unopened immature flower buds, are diced and used as a cooking ingredient, and the flowers are edible and can be used in salads. Chives are a rich source of vitamin A, folate, vitamin C, and vitamin K, and a good source of iron, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Cilantro
Description: Cilantro is also known as coriander, or Chinese parsley. All parts of the plant are edible, but the fresh leaves and the dried seeds are the parts most traditionally used in cooking. The leaves have a different taste from the seeds, with citrus overtones. Different people may perceive the taste of coriander differently; some finding it refreshing and lemony, whereas others characterize it as soapy or rotten. Leaves are particularly rich in vitamin A, vitamin C and vitamin K. Seeds provide significant amounts of dietary fiber, calcium, selenium, iron, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Citrus
Description: Citrus is a genus of flowering trees and shrubs in the rue family, Rutaceae. Plants in the genus produce citrus fruits, including important crops like oranges, lemons, grapefruit, pomelo and limes. They are eaten fresh and typically peeled and can be easily split into segments.

Name: Clementines
Description: A clementine is a tangor, which is a hybrid between a willowleaf mandarin orange and a sweet orange. The exterior is a deep orange color with a smooth, glossy appearance. Similar to tangerines, they are usually easy to peel. Clementines are typically juicy and sweet, with less acid than oranges. They are a rich source of vitamin C but do not have any significant content of other micronutrients.

Name: Collard Greens
Description: Collard greens, or collards, are certain loose-leafed varieties of plants in the cabbage family. The name collard comes from the word colewort, the name of the wild cabbage plant. The plants are grown for their large, dark-colored, edible leaves. Collards are available year-round, but are tastier and more nutritious in the cold months, after the first frost. They contain substantial amounts of vitamin K, and are rich sources of vitamin A, vitamin C, and manganese, and moderate sources of calcium and vitamin B6.

Name: Corn
Description: Maize, also known as corn, is a cereal grain first domesticated by indigenous peoples in Southern Mexico about 10,000 years ago. Maize has become a staple food in many parts of the world, with total production surpassing that of wheat or rice. Raw, yellow, sweet maize kernels are a good source thiamin, niacin, pantothenic acid and folate, and a moderate source of dietary fiber, magnesium and phosphorous.

Name: Cranberries
Description: Cranberries are a group of evergreen dwarf shrubs and can be found in acidic bogs throughout the cooler regions of the Northern Hemisphere. As fresh cranberries are hard, sour, and bitter, about 95% of cranberries are processed and used to make cranberry juice and sauce. They are also sold dried and sweetened. Raw cranberries have moderate levels of vitamin C, dietary fiber and the essential dietary mineral, manganese, as well as other essential micronutrients in minor amounts.

Name: Cucumbers
Description: Cucumber is a widely cultivated plant in the gourd family, originating in India. Botanically speaking, the cucumber is classified as a type of berry with a hard outer rind and no internal divisions. Much like tomato and squash, it is often perceived, prepared and eaten as a vegetable. Cucumber fruits consist of 95% water, are a good source of vitamin K but supply low content of other essential nutrients.

Name: Currants
Description: The blackcurrant is a woody shrub grown for its piquant berries. They can be eaten raw but are usually cooked in a variety of sweet or savoury dishes. They are used to make jams, jellies and syrups and are grown commercially for the juice market. Blackcurrant is native to temperate parts of central and northern Europe and northern Asia where it prefers damp fertile soils. The raw fruit is particularly rich in vitamin C, and moderate levels of iron and manganese. Other nutrients are present in negligible amounts

Name: Dates
Description: Fossil records show that the date palm has existed for at least 50 million years. Dates have been a staple food of the Middle East and the Indus Valley for thousands of years. Date fruits range from bright red to bright yellow in color, depending on variety. Dates provide a wide range of essential nutrients, and are a very good source of potassium. The sugar content of ripe dates is about 80%, and also offer protein, fiber, and trace elements including boron, cobalt, copper, fluorine, magnesium, manganese, selenium, and zinc.

Name: Edamame
Description: Edamame is a preparation of immature soybeans in the pod, found in cuisines with origins in East Asia. The pods are boiled or steamed and may be served with salt. In Japan, they are usually blanched with salt water and so not served with salt. When the beans are outside the pod, the term mukimame is sometimes used. Edamame is rich in protein, dietary fiber, and micronutrients, particularly folate, manganese, phosphorus, and vitamin K.

Name: Eggplant
Description: Eggplant is a species of nightshade grown for its edible fruit. Eggplant is the common name in North America, Australia and New Zealand; in British English, it is aubergine, and in South Asia and South Africa, brinjal. The fruit is widely used in cooking and is related to the tomato and potato. The egg-shaped, glossy, purple fruit has white flesh with a meaty texture. It provides low amounts of essential nutrients, with only manganese having moderate content.

Name: Endive
Description: Endive is a leaf vegetable belonging to the sunflower family, which includes several bitter leafed vegetables. There are two main varieties; curly endive or frisee, often called chicory in the United States, and escarole, or broad-leaved endive. Endive is rich in many vitamins and minerals, especially in folate and vitamin A and vitamin K, and is high in fiber.

Name: Fava Beans
Description: Fava beans, also known as the broad bean, faba bean, field bean, bell bean, or tic bean, is a species of flowering plant in the pea family. The fruit is a broad, leathery pod, initially green but maturing to blackish-brown, with a densely downy surface. Each pod contains three to eight seeds. Fava beans are of uncertain origin but widely cultivated as a crop. They are a rich source of thiamine, riboflavin, niacin, vitamin B6, and folate, as well as several dietary minerals, especially iron, manganese, magnesium, phosphorus, potassium and zinc.

Name: Fennel
Description: Fennel is a flowering plant species in the carrot family. It is a hardy, perennial herb with yellow flowers and feathery leaves. It is a highly aromatic and flavorful herb with culinary and medicinal uses, and along with similar-tasting anise, is one of the primary ingredients of absinthe. Fennel seeds are a rich source of protein, dietary fiber, B vitamins, vitamin C and several dietary minerals, especially calcium, iron, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Fiddleheads
Description: Fiddleheads or fiddlehead greens are the coiled fronds of a young fern, harvested for use as a vegetable. Fiddleheads have been part of traditional diets in much of Northern France since the beginning of the Middle Ages, across Asia, and also among Native Americans for centuries. Fiddleheads contain various vitamins and minerals, as well as omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids, and are a source of antioxidants and dietary fiber. They are low in sodium, but rich in potassium, which may make them suitable for people who need a low-sodium diet

Name: Figs
Description: The common fig is an Asian species of flowering plant in the mulberry family, native to the Middle East and western Asia. Figs can be eaten fresh or dried, with most commercial production being in dried or otherwise processed forms, since the ripe fruit does not transport or keep well. Raw figs are a good source of dietary fiber, but otherwise do not supply essential nutrients in significant amounts. Dried figs are a rich source of dietary fiber and the essential mineral manganese, while several other dietary minerals are in moderate-to-low content.

Name: Garlic
Description: Garlic is a species in the onion family. Its close relatives include the onion, shallot, leek, chive, and Chinese onion. The garlic plant bulb is the most commonly used part of the plant. The bulbs are normally divided into numerous fleshy sections called cloves. Garlic is widely used around the world for its characteristic pungent, spicy flavor that mellows and sweetens considerably with cooking. Garlic is a rich source of vitamin B6, vitamin C, manganese and phosphorus, and a good source of thiamin, vitamin B5, calcium, iron and zinc.

Name: Garlic Scapes
Description: Garlic scapes are the flower bud of the garlic plant, and are also known as garlic spears, stems, or tops. Immature scapes are tender and edible. Scapes generally have a milder taste than garlic cloves.

Name: Ginger
Description: Ginger likely originated in regions from the Indian subcontinent to southern Asia. Ginger root produces a hot, fragrant kitchen spice. Young ginger roots are juicy and fleshy with a mild taste, whereas mature ginger roots are fibrous and nearly dry. Fresh ginger can be substituted for ground ginger at a ratio of 6:1, although the flavors of fresh and dried ginger are somewhat different. Ginger is a good source of vitamin B6, magnesium and manganese.

Name: Gooseberries
Description: Gooseberries are native to Europe, the Caucasus and northern Africa. Gooseberries can be eaten as-is, or used as an ingredient in desserts, such as pies, fools and crumbles. Early pickings are generally sour and more appropriate for culinary use. They are an excellent source of vitamin C but offer no other nutrients in significant content.

Name: Grapefruit
Description: The grapefruit is a subtropical citrus tree known for its sour to semi-sweet, somewhat bitter fruit. Grapefruit is a hybrid cross between sweet orange and pomelo. The grapefruit's name refers to clusters of the fruit on the tree, which can appear similar to that of grapes. Grapefruit is a rich source of vitamin C, contains the fiber pectin, and the pink and red hues contain beneficial antioxidants.

Name: Grapes
Description: Grapes are botanically a berry. The cultivation of the domesticated grape began 6,000‚Äì8,000 years ago in the Near East. Yeast occurs naturally on the skins of grapes, which led to the discovery of alcoholic drinks such as wine. Cultivated grapes are usually classified as either table grapes to be eaten raw, which tend to be larger and seedless, or wine grapes to make wine, which are smaller, seeded and have thicker skins. Grapes are a good source of vitamin K but offer little by way of other nutrients.

Name: Green Beans
Description: Green beans, also known as French beans, string beans, snap beans, and snaps, are the unripe, young fruit and protective pods of various varieties of the common bean. Green beans are harvested and consumed with their enclosing pods, typically before the seeds inside have fully matured. Naturally bean pods contain a fibrous string running the length of the pod, which must be removed before eating. The first stringless bean was bred in 1894 and most modern varieties do not have strings.  Green beans are a good source of vitamin B6, vitamin C, vitamin K and manganese.

Name: Green Onions
Description: Green onions are also known as scallions and salad onion. Green onions have a milder taste than most onions. The leaves are used as a vegetable either raw or cooked. Spring onions are also known as green onions, but are in fact very young onions, harvested before the bulb has had a chance to swell.

Name: Ground Cherries
Description: Ground Cherries are also known as the Inca berry, Cape gooseberry, poha berries, and golden berries. Not all groundcherry species bear edible fruit but some do and their fruit is similar to a firm tomato in texture, and like strawberries or pineapple in flavor with a mild acidity. They can be eaten raw and used in salads. Some varieties are added to desserts, used as flavoring, made into fruit preserves, or dried and used like raisins.

Name: Horseradish
Description: Horseradish is a perennial plant of the cabbage family, its root used as a spice. The intact horseradish root has hardly any aroma but when cut or grated enzymes release the distinctive pungent flavor. Horseradish sauce made from grated horseradish root and vinegar is a popular condiment in the United Kingdom and in Poland and is served with roast beef. Horseradish supplies no significant nutrient content.

Name: Jicama
Description: Jicama, is also known as Spanish j√≠cama, Mexican yam bean, or Mexican turnip.  It is a native Mexican vine, although the name usually refers to the plant's edible root. The flavor is sweet and starchy, reminiscent of some apples or raw green beans, and it is usually eaten raw. It is also cooked in soups and stir-fried dishes. J√≠cama is high in carbohydrates in the form of dietary fiber and is a good source of vitamin C.

Name: Kale
Description: Kale or leaf cabbage are certain varieties of cabbage grown for their edible leaves. Until the end of the Middle Ages, kale was one of the most common green vegetables in Europe. Kale contains a large amount of vitamin K, is a rich source of vitamin A, vitamin C, vitamin B6, folate, and manganese and a good source of other trace nutrients.

Name: Kiwi
Description: Kiwifruit, often abbreviated as kiwi, is also known as the Chinese gooseberry and is native to north-central and eastern China. Kiwifruit may be eaten raw, made into juices, used in baked goods, prepared with meat or used as a garnish. The whole fruit is suitable for human consumption, however the skin is often discarded due to its texture. It is particularly rich in vitamin C and vitamin K, has a moderate content of vitamin E, but has not other significant micronutrients.

Name: Kohlrabi
Description: Kohlrabi, also known as the German turnip or turnip cabbage, is a biennial vegetable and both the stems and leaves can be eaten. Kohlrabi stems have two distinct fibrous layers that are generally peeled away prior to cooking or serving raw. The bulbous stem is frequently used raw in salad or slaws. The leaves are edible and can be used interchangeably with collard greens and kale. Kohlrabi is a rich source of vitamin C and a good source of vitamin B6.

Name: Lamb's Quarters
Description: Lamb's quarter is another name for various edible species of goosefoot, or pigweed. The goosefoot family contains several plants used as leaf vegetables in the manner of the closely related spinach. The goosefoot family also includes quinoa, which has increasing importance in a gluten-free diet.

Name: Lavender
Description: Lavender is native to the Old World and is found across Europe, the Mediterranean, North Africa, and southwest Asia to southeast India. As an aromatic, it has a sweet fragrance with a taste of lemon or citrus notes. It is used as a spice or condiment in pastas, salads and dressings, and desserts. Lavender buds and greens are used to flavor savory dishes and in teas.

Name: Leeks
Description: Leeks have a mild, onion-like taste. In its raw state, the vegetable is crunchy and firm. Boiling turns it soft and mild in taste, frying leaves it crunchier and preserves the taste. The edible portions of the leek are the white base of the leaves, the upper green leaves usually being discarded. Archaeological evidence indicates that the leek was a part of the Egyptian diet from at least the second millennium BCE.  Leeks are a rich source of vitamin K, and a good source of vitamin B6, folate, vitamin C, iron and manganese.

Name: Lemongrass
Description: Lemongrass is a genus of Asian, African and Australian plants in the grass family. Lemongrass is widely used as a culinary herb in Asian cuisines and also as medicinal herb in India. It has a subtle citrus flavor and can be dried and powdered, or used fresh. It is commonly used in teas, soups, and curries, and is also suitable for use with poultry, fish, beef, and seafood.

Name: Lemons
Description: The origin of the lemon is unknown, though lemons are thought to have first grown in northeast India, northern Burma or China. The juice of the lemon is about 5% to 6% citric acid, with a pH of around 2.2, about five times the amount of citric acid found in orange juice. Lemons are a rich source of vitamin C, but have insignificant amounts of other essential nutrients.

Name: Lettuce
Description: Lettuce is an annual plant in the daisy family. Generally grown as a hardy annual, lettuce is easily cultivated, although it requires relatively low temperatures to prevent it from flowering quickly. It is a rich source of vitamin K and vitamin A, and a moderate source of folate and iron. Lettuce was first cultivated by the ancient Egyptians.

Name: Lima Beans
Description: Lima bean is also known as butter bean, sieva bean, or Madagascar bean, and is native to South America. Lima beans are a good source of dietary fiber, and a virtually fat-free source of high-quality protein, as well as a good source of vitamin B6, folate, and manganese. Like many beans, raw lima beans are toxic if not boiled for at least 10 minutes. The high fiber content in lima beans prevents blood sugar levels from rising too rapidly after eating them which makes them a good choice for people with diabetes.

Name: Mandarins
Description: Mandarins are generally peeled and eaten fresh. The fresh fruit is also used in salads, desserts and main dishes. The peel is used fresh, whole or zested, or dried as chenpi, and can be used as a spice for cooking, baking, drinks, or candy. Clementines and tangerines are hybrids of mandarins. The fruits contain a large amount of sugar and are a rich source of vitamins C.

Name: Mangoes
Description: Mangoes are juicy stone fruit, or drupe, from numerous species of tropical trees related to the cashew. Sour, unripe mangoes are used in chutneys and pickles, or may be eaten raw with salt, chili, or soy sauce. Ripe mangoes can be eaten raw and are used raw and cooked in many cuisines around the world. Mango leaves, stem, sap and skin have the potential to cause contact dermatitis in susceptible people. Mango is a rich source of vitamin C and a good source of folate.

Name: Melons
Description: A melon fruit is actually a kind of berry. Melons originated in Africa and southwest Asia, and began to appear in Europe toward the end of the Western Roman Empire. Melons were among the earliest plants to be domesticated in both the Old and New Worlds. Fresh cantaloupe is a rich source of vitamin C and vitamin A, with other nutrients in negligible amounts.

Name: Mint
Description: Mints are aromatic, almost exclusively perennial, rarely annual herbs. The leaves have a warm, fresh, aromatic, sweet flavor with a cool aftertaste, and are used in teas, beverages, jellies, syrups, candies, and ice creams. In Middle Eastern, British and American cuisine, mint is used on lamb dishes.

Name: Morels
Description: Morels are a type of edible sac fungi with a distinctive honeycomb appearance. They are a feature of many cuisines, including Proven√ßal, and their unique flavor is prized by chefs worldwide, with recipes and preparation methods designed to highlight and preserve it. As with most edible fungi, they are best when collected in the wild or bought fresh. Morels are known to contain heat sensitive toxins, so they must always be cooked before eating.

Name: Mushrooms
Description: A mushroom is the fleshy, spore-bearing fruiting body of a fungus. The standard for the name mushroom is the cultivated white button mushroom, but can be applied to a wide variety of edible fungi. Raw mushrooms are a rich source of B vitamins, selenium and copper, and a moderate source of phosphorus, zinc and potassium.

Name: Mustard Greens
Description: Mustard greens are also known as brown mustard, Chinese mustard, Indian mustard, leaf mustard, Oriental mustard and vegetable mustard. The leaves, seeds, and stems are edible. Mustard greens are a rich source of vitamins A, C and K and are a moderate source of vitamin E and calcium.

Name: Nectarines
Description: Peaches and nectarines are the same species, with nectarines having a recessive gene for smooth skin. Nectarines, along with cherries, plums and apricots, are stone fruits or drupes.  Nectarines are best stored at temperatures of 32¬∞F and high humidity. They are highly perishable, and typically consumed or canned within two weeks of harvest. Nectarines contains small amounts of essential nutrients, but none is a significant proportion of the Daily Value.

Name: Nettles
Description: Stinging nettle is a rhizomatous perennial plant originally from Europe and Asia. The entire plant is covered with tiny, stinging hairs and so should never be consumed raw. Nettles have a flavour similar to spinach mixed with cucumber when cooked, and are rich in vitamins A and C, iron, potassium, manganese, and calcium. Soaking stinging nettles in water or cooking removes the stinging chemicals from the plant.

Name: Nopales
Description: Nopal is a common name in Mexican Spanish for Opuntia cacti, commonly referred to in English as prickly pear. The nopal pads can be eaten raw or cooked, used in marmalades, soups stews and salads. Nopales have a light, slightly tart flavor, like green beans, and a crisp texture. They are an excellent source of manganese and a good source of vitamin C.

Name: Okra
Description: Okra or okro is also known as ladies' fingers or ochro. Okra leaves may be cooked or eaten raw in salads. Okra seeds may be roasted and ground to form a caffeine-free substitute for coffee. Pods are cooked, pickled, eaten raw, or included in salads. The products of the plant are mucilaginous, resulting in the characteristic goo or slime when the seed pods are cooked. Raw okra is rich in dietary fiber, vitamin C and vitamin K, with moderate contents of thiamin, folate and magnesium.

Name: Olives
Description: The olive tree is an evergreen tree or shrub native to the Mediterranean, Asia, and Africa. Olive trees can be very long lived and many trees have been dated to over 1500 years old. About 90% of harvested olives are turned into oil, with the rest eaten as table olives. Green and black olives are the same fruit, black olives being fully ripe. Olives are a rich source of vitamin E, and contain a large amount of sodium but other nutrients are insignificant.

Name: Onions
Description: The onion is a close relative of garlic, shallot, leek, chive and Chinese onion. The onion is most frequently a biennial or a perennial plant, but is usually treated as an annual and harvested in its first growing season. It is unclear where onions originated but food uses of onions date back thousands of years in China, Egypt and Persia. Onions contain low amounts of essential nutrients and so contribute savoury flavour to dishes without contributing significant caloric or nutritional content.

Name: Oranges
Description: The orange, also called sweet orange, is a hybrid between pomelo and mandarin. As with other citrus fruits, orange pulp is an excellent source of vitamin C, and numerous other essential nutrients are present in low amounts. Although not as juicy or tasty as the flesh, orange peel is also edible and nutritious.

Name: Oregano
Description: Oregano is a flowering plant in the mint family native to temperate Western and Southwestern Eurasia and the Mediterranean region. The herb is widely used in cuisines of the Mediterranean Basin, the Philippines, and Latin America, especially in Argentinian cuisine. Oregano leaves can be more flavourful when dried than fresh.

Name: Papaya
Description: The papaya, papaw, or pawpaw is native to Mexico and northern South America. The fruit is a large berry and is ripe when it feels soft. Ripe papaya is eaten raw, without skin or seeds, and unripe green fruit can be eaten cooked. It is a significant source of vitamin C and a moderate source of folate, but otherwise has low content of nutrients. Green papaya is rich in papain which is used for tenderizing meat.

Name: Parsley
Description: Parsley is a leafy, flowering biennial plant in temperate climates, or an annual herb in subtropical and tropical areas. It is native to the central Mediterranean region. Parsley is also grown as a root vegetable. It is used as a garnish in many cuisines and root parsley is common in central and Eastern European dishes.

Name: Parsnips
Description: The parsnip is a root vegetable closely related to the carrot and parsley. It is native to Eurasia and was cultivated by the Romans. It was used as a sweetener before the arrival of cane sugar in Europe. The parsnip is rich in vitamins and minerals, and is particularly rich in potassium. Several of the B-group vitamins are present, but levels of vitamin C are reduced in cooking. Since most of the vitamins and minerals are found close to the skin, much of its nutritional content will be lost unless the root is finely peeled or cooked whole.

Name: Pea Shoots
Description: Pea shoots are the young and tender shoots and leaves of the pea vine. They retain the taste of fresh peas. They can be eaten raw in salads and can be cooked, and are especially good when cooked quickly and simply in stir fries.

Name: Peaches
Description: The peach is native to Northwest China and was domesticated as early as 6000 BC. Low-acid white-fleshed peaches are the most popular kinds in China, Japan, and neighbouring Asian countries, while Europeans and North Americans have historically favoured the acidic, yellow-fleshed varieties. Peaches continue to ripen after being picked from the tree. They contains small amounts of essential nutrients, but none as a significant proportion of the Daily Value.

Name: Peanuts
Description: The peanut is also known as the groundnut or the goobe. It is not a true nut but rather a legume and, because of its high oil content, is also classified as an oil crop. Peanuts are very nutritious, high in calories they provide several B vitamins, vitamin E, manganese, magnesium, phosphorus and dietary fiber. They also provide a higher proportion of protein than many tree nuts.

Name: Pears
Description: Pears, like several other common fruits, are part of the rose family. The pear is native to coastal and mildly temperate regions of western Europe and north Africa, and east across Asia. Pears ripen at room temperature and will ripen faster if placed next to bananas in a fruit bowl. Pears supply carbohydrates, and are a good source of dietary fiber, but otherwise provide no essential nutrients in significant amounts.

Name: Peas
Description: Peas are native to the Mediterranean basin and the Near East. In early times, peas were grown mostly for their dry seeds, whereas green garden peas, eaten immature and fresh, were an innovative luxury of the early 17th Century. Peas are starchy, but high in fiber, protein, vitamin A, vitamin B6, vitamin C, vitamin K, phosphorus, magnesium, copper, iron, zinc and lutein.

Name: Pecans
Description: The pecan is native to Mexico and the Southern United States. Pecans are not truly a nut, but are technically a drupe, a fruit with a single stone or pit, surrounded by a husk. They can be eaten fresh or used in cooking, particularly in sweet desserts. Pecans are also a major ingredient in praline candy. Pecans are very high is calories and fat, are a rich source of dietary fiber, manganese, magnesium, phosphorus, zinc and thiamin. They are also a good source of protein, iron, and B vitamins.

Name: Peppers
Description: The bell pepper is also known as sweet pepper or capsicum. Peppers are native to Mexico, Central America, and northern South America. Botanically speaking, bell peppers are fruits. The bell pepper is the only member of the genus that does not produce capsaicin, the chemical that gives chili its hotness. Bell peppers are a moderate source of vitamin B6, a rich source of vitamin C, and red peppers contain more vitamin C than green peppers.

Name: Persimmons
Description: Persimmons can be eaten fresh, dried, raw, or cooked. There are two types of persimmon: astringent which contain very high levels of soluble tannins and are unpalatable if eaten before completely softened, and non-astringent which may be consumed when still very firm and remain edible when very soft. Persimmons have high levels of dietary fiber but do not offer a significant source of nutrients except for manganese and provitamin A beta-carotene.

Name: Pineapple
Description: The pineapple is a tropical plant and the fruit consists of coalesced berries. The pineapple is indigenous to South America and is said to originate from the area between southern Brazil and Paraguay. Pineapples are an excellent source of vitamin C and manganese, and are rich in bromelain which is used as a meat tenderizer, and which is responsible for the sore mouth feeling often experienced when eating it.

Name: Pistachios
Description: The pistachio is a member of the cashew family. Pistachio trees are alternate-bearing or biennial-bearing, meaning the harvest is heavier in alternate years. Pistachios are a nutritionally dense food high in calories, protein, dietary fiber, and vitamins; especially thiamin and vitamin B6.  They are also a good source of calcium, riboflavin, vitamin B5, folate, vitamin E , and vitamin K.

Name: Plums
Description: Plum fruit ranges from sweet to tart, the skin may be particularly tart, and the fruit can be eaten fresh or dried. Plums may have been one of the first fruits domesticated by humans and plum remains have been found in Neolithic age archaeological sites. Plums are a moderate source of vitamin C, with no other nutrients in significant content.

Name: Pomegranates
Description: The pomegranate is a fruit-bearing deciduous shrub, originated in the region extending from modern-day Iran to northern India and has been cultivated throughout the Middle East, South Asia, and Mediterranean region for several millennia. Botanically, the edible fruit is a berry. They are a good source of vitamin C, vitamin K and folate, and the seeds are a rich source of dietary fiber.

Name: Potatoes
Description: Potato plants are herbaceous perennials and part of the nightshade family. The potato was first domesticated in the Andes between 8000 and 5000 BC and the Spanish introduced the potato to Europe in the second half of the 16th century. They are a rich source of vitamin B6 and vitamin C and are considered to have a high glycemic index.

Name: Pummelo
Description: The pummelo, also called pomello, pommelo, pumelo, pamplemousse, Jambola or shaddock, is a non-hybrid citrus fruit, similar in appearance to a large grapefruit, native to South and Southeast Asia. The fruit tastes like a sweet, mild grapefruit although it is much larger than a grapefruit, and also has a much thicker rind. They are an excellent source of vitamin C. Pomelos exhibit the same negative interactions with certain drugs as grapefruits do.

Name: Pumpkin
Description: Pumpkin is a squash plant native to North America. Most parts of the pumpkin are edible, including the fleshy shell, the seeds, the leaves, and even the flowers. When ripe, the pumpkin can be boiled, steamed, or roasted. It is an excellent source of provitamin A beta-carotene and vitamin A.

Name: Purslane
Description: Purslane, also known as verdolaga, red root, or pursley is an annual succulent. The stems, leaves and flower buds are all edible and it is widely used in East Mediterranean countries. It has a slightly sour and salty taste and may be used fresh as a salad, stir-fried, or cooked in the same manner as spinach. Because of its mucilaginous quality it also is suitable for soups and stews. Purslane is a good source of vitamin A, vitamin C, vitamin E, vitamin B, carotenoids, and dietary minerals such as magnesium, calcium, potassium, and iron.

Name: Quince
Description: Quince is a deciduous tree that bears a fruit similar in appearance to a pear. The fruit have an intense aroma and flavor but most varieties of quince are too hard and tart to be eaten raw. However they may be cooked or roasted and used for jams, marmalade, jellies, or pudding.  Quince is a moderate source of vitamin C.

Name: Radicchio
Description: Radicchio is a perennial cultivated form of leaf chicory sometimes known as Italian chicory because modern cultivation began in Italy. Radicchio has a bitter and spicy taste, which mellows if it is grilled or roasted. In Italian cuisine, it is usually eaten grilled in olive oil, or mixed into dishes such as risotto. Its roots, after roasting and grinding, can be used as a coffee substitute or coffee additive.  Radicchio is very good source of vitamin K.

Name: Radishes
Description: The radish is an edible root vegetable of the mustard family that was domesticated in Europe in pre-Roman times. The bulb of the radish is usually eaten raw, and the flesh has a crisp texture and a pungent, peppery flavor. But the entire plant is edible and the tops can be used as a leaf vegetable. The seed can also be sprouted and eaten raw in a similar manner to mung beans.

Name: Ramps
Description: Ramps, also known as spring onion, ramson, wild leek, and wild garlic, is a North American species of wild onion. It is regarded as an early spring vegetable with a strong garlic-like odor and a pronounced onion flavor.

Name: Rapini
Description: Rapini, also known as broccoli raab or broccoli rabe, is a green cruciferous vegetable, related to the cabbage, with edible leave, buds, and stems. The flavor of rapini is nutty, bitter, and pungent and also reminiscent of mustard greens. It is particularly associated with Italian, and Portuguese cuisines.  It is an excellent source of vitamin K, a rich source of folate and vitamin C, and a good source of vitamin A, thiamine, riboflavin, vitamin B6, iron, manganese and phosphorus.

Name: Raspberries
Description: The raspberry is the edible fruit of a selection of plant species in the rose family. All varieties of raspberries have perennial roots but most raspberries have shoots that are biennial. Raspberries are a rich source of vitamin C and manganese. The aggregate fruit structure adds to raspberry's nutritional value, as it greatly increases the proportion of dietary fiber. Raspberry leaves can be used fresh or dried in herbal teas, providing an astringent flavor.

Name: Rhubarb
Description: Rhubarb is a herbaceous perennial plant growing from short, thick rhizomes. Leaf stalks are crisp with a strong, tart taste. Although rhubarb is not a true fruit, in the kitchen it is usually prepared as if it were, the stalks are often cut into small pieces and stewed with added sugar. Rhubarb leaves contain poisonous substances, including oxalic acid, and so should never be eaten; the roots and stalks also contain oxalic acid but in such small quantities as to be harmless.

Name: Rosemary
Description: Rosemary is an aromatic evergreen shrub and is a member of the mint family. The name rosemary derives from the Latin for dew of the sea. It is native to the Mediterranean and Asia. The leaves have a bitter, astringent taste and a characteristic aroma which complements many cooked foods, such as roast lamb, pork, chicken and turkey.

Name: Rutabaga
Description: The rutabaga, swede or neep, is a root vegetable that originated as a cross between the cabbage and the turnip. The roots are prepared for human consumption in a variety of ways, roasted, baked, boiled, uncooked and thinly julienned as a side dish or in a salad. The leaves can be eaten as a leaf vegetable. Rutabaga contains significant amounts of vitamin C.

Name: Sage
Description: Sage is a member of the mint family and native to the Mediterranean region. In Britain, sage has for generations been listed as one of the essential herbs, along with parsley, rosemary, and thyme, as referred to in the folk song Scarborough Fair. It has a savory, slightly peppery flavor. It appears in many cuisines, notably Italian, Balkan and Middle Eastern cookery.

Name: Salsify
Description: Salsify is commonly known as oyster plant, Jerusalem star or goatsbeard. It is a common biennial wildflower, native to Mediterranean regions of Europe. The root, and sometimes the young shoots are used as a vegetable. The root is noted for tasting of oysters, but more insipid with a touch of sweetness. The young shoots of purple salsify can also be eaten, as well as young leaves .

Name: Shallots
Description: The shallot is a type of onion, probably originating in Central or Southwest Asia. Shallots appear to contain more flavonoids and phenols than other members of the onion family. Shallots are used in cooking in addition to being pickled. Finely sliced, deep-fried shallots are used as a condiment in Asian cuisine, often served with porridge. Fresh shallots can be stored in cool, dry area for six months or longer.

Name: Shell Beans
Description: Shell beans are any of the varieties of beans whose pods are removed and typically not eaten. Popular varieties include fava or broad beans, cranberry or borlotti beans, lima beans, chickpeas or garbanzo beans, black beans, and scarlet runner beans. Fresh shell beans have a sweet and creamy taste and can be prepared in the same ways as their dried counterparts, but take less time to cook.

Name: Snap Peas
Description: The snap pea, also known as the sugar snap pea, is an edible-podded pea. The snap pea differs from the snow pea in that their pods are rounded as opposed to flat. The name mangetout can apply both to snap peas and snow peas. Snap peas are often served in salads or eaten whole. They may also be stir-fried or steamed. Before being eaten, mature snap pea pods may need to be "stringed", removing the membranous string running along the top of the pod from base to tip.

Name: Snow Peas
Description: The snow pea is a variety of pea eaten whole in its pod while still unripe. They can be grown in open fields during cool seasons and so can be cultivated during winter and spring seasons. Snow peas, along with sugar snap peas and unlike field and garden peas, are notable for having edible pods that lack inedible fiber, or "strings". The stems and leaves of the immature plant are used as a vegetable in Chinese cooking.

Name: Sorrel
Description: Common sorrel or garden sorrel is a perennial herb. It is a common plant in grassland habitats and is cultivated as a garden herb or salad vegetable. The leaves may be pur√©ed in soups and sauces or added to salads; they have a flavour that is similar to kiwifruit or sour wild strawberries. The plant's sharp taste is due to oxalic acid, which is mildly toxic.

Name: Spinach
Description: Spinach is an edible flowering plant native to central and western Asia. It is a rich source of vitamin A, vitamin C, vitamin K, magnesium, manganese, iron and folate. It is also is a good source of the B vitamins riboflavin and vitamin B6, vitamin E, calcium, potassium, and dietary fiber. Fresh spinach loses much of its nutritional value with storage of more than a few days, although refrigeration slows this effect to about eight days.

Name: Sprouts
Description: Sprouting is the practice of germinating seeds so they can be eaten raw or cooked. Many seed types can be used as sprouts but mung beans, soy beans and alfalfa are commonly used. The sprouted beans are more nutritious than the original beans and require much less cooking time. Sprouts are said to be rich in digestible energy, bioavailable vitamins, minerals, amino acids, proteins, and phytochemicals, as these are necessary for a germinating plant to grow.

Name: Strawberries
Description: The first garden strawberry was grown in Brittany, France during the late 18th century as a result of a cross of varieties from North America and Chile. Prior to this, wild strawberries and cultivated selections from wild strawberry species were the common source of the fruit. The strawberry is an excellent source of vitamin C, a good source of manganese, and provides several other vitamins and dietary minerals in lesser amounts.

Name: Summer Squash
Description: Summer squash are squashes that are harvested when immature, while the rind is still tender and edible. The name summer squash refers to the short storage life of these squashes, unlike that of winter squashes. Summer squash include Cousa squash, scallop squash, tromboncino or zucchetta, crookneck squash, straightneck squash, and zucchini.

Name: Sunchokes
Description: The sunchoke, also called sunroot, Jerusalem artichoke, earth apple, or topinambour, is a species of sunflower native to eastern North America. They are rich in the carbohydrate inulin and sunchoke tubers stored for any length of time convert their inulin into its component fructose, which gives them a sweet taste. Sunchoke are high in potassium and iron, and have significant amounts of niacin, thiamine, phosphorus, and copper.

Name: Sweet Potatoes
Description: The sweet potato belongs to the bindweed or morning glory family. Its large tuberous roots are starchy and sweet-tasting, and the young leaves and shoots are sometimes eaten as greens. The origin and domestication of sweet potato is thought to be in either Central America or South America. Sweet potatoes are rich in complex carbohydrates, dietary fiber and beta-carotene, while having moderate contents of other micronutrients, including vitamin B5, vitamin B6 and manganese.

Name: Tangerines
Description: The tangerine is a group of orange-colored citrus fruit consisting of hybrids of the mandarin orange. The name was first used for fruit coming from Tangier, Morocco. Tangerines are smaller and less rounded than common oranges. The taste is considered less sour, as well as sweeter and stronger, than that of an orange. Tangerines contain 85% water, 13% carbohydrates, and negligible amounts of fat and protein. Only vitamin C is present in significant nutritional content.

Name: Taro
Description: Taro is a perennial, tropical plant primarily grown as a root vegetable for its edible starchy corm, but also as a leaf vegetable. In its raw form, the plant is toxic, however, the toxin can be minimized and the tuber rendered palatable by cooking, or by steeping in cold water overnight. The corms are roasted, baked or boiled, and the natural sugars give a sweet nutty flavor. Young taro leaves and stems can be eaten after boiling twice to remove the acrid flavor, and the leaves are a good source of vitamins A and C.

Name: Tarragon
Description: Tarragon, also known as estragon, is a species of perennial herb in the sunflower family. It is widespread in the wild across much of Eurasia and North America. Tarragon has an aromatic property reminiscent of anise. It is one of the four 'fines herbes' of French cooking, is particularly suitable for chicken, fish, and egg dishes, and is the main flavoring component of B√©arnaise sauce.

Name: Thyme
Description: Thyme is an aromatic perennial evergreen herb with culinary, medicinal, and ornamental uses. Thyme is part of the mint family, and a relative of oregano. Thyme is sold both fresh and dried. The fresh form is more flavourful, but also less convenient as storage life is rarely more than a week. Thyme retains its flavour on drying better than many other herbs.

Name: Tomatillos
Description: The tomatillo, or Mexican husk tomato, is a member of the nightshade family bearing small, spherical green or green-purple fruit. These fruit can be eaten raw or cooked. For salsa verde, it is harvested early, when the fruit is sour. When picked later, the fruit is seedier, has a sweeter taste and is suitable as a tomato substitute. Tomatillos can also be dried to enhance the sweetness of the fruit, and are similar to dried cranberries with a hint of tomato flavour.

Name: Tomatoes
Description: The tomato is the fruit, botanically a berry, of the tomato plant which is part of the nightshade family. The species originated in western South America. A tomato is 95% water, contains 4% carbohydrates and less than 1% each of fat and protein.  They are a moderate source of vitamin C, but otherwise are absent of significant nutrients.

Name: Turnips
Description: The turnip is a biennial root vegetable commonly grown in temperate climates worldwide for its white, bulbous taproot. The turnip's root is high in vitamin C. The green leaves of the turnip top, also referred to as turnip greens, resemble mustard greens in flavor, and are a good source of vitamin A, folate, vitamin C, vitamin K and calcium.

Name: Watercress
Description: Watercress is a rapidly growing, aquatic or semi-aquatic, perennial plant native to Europe and Asia, and one of the oldest known leaf vegetables consumed by humans. It is botanically related to garden cress, mustard, radish, and wasabi - all notable for their piquant flavor. Watercress is particularly rich in vitamin K, and contains significant amounts of vitamin A, vitamin C, riboflavin, vitamin B6, calcium, and manganese.

Name: Watermelon
Description: Watermelon is a scrambling and trailing vine in the flowering gourd family. Watermelon is grown in tropical and subtropical areas worldwide for its large edible fruit, which is a special kind of berry. Watermelons are a sweet, popular fruit of summer, usually consumed fresh in slices, diced in mixed fruit salads, or as juice. There is evidence of watermelon cultivation in Ancient Egypt from seeds found in tombs.

Name: Winter Squash
Description: Winter squash is an annual fruit representing several squash species. It differs from summer squash in that it is harvested and eaten in the mature fruit stage when the seeds within have matured fully and the skin has hardened into a tough rind. Winter squash is a low-calorie food and a good source of complex vegetable carbohydrates and dietary fiber. It is an excellent source of vitamin A, and a rich source of vitamin C, potassium, and manganese.

Name: Yams
Description: Yam is the common name for several species of perennial herbaceous vines cultivated for their starchy tubers in many temperate and subtropical regions around the world. Yam tubers can grow up to 50ft in length. In parts of the United States and Canada, yam is sometimes used to refer to varieties of the unrelated sweet potato.  Raw yam has only moderate nutrient density, with appreciable content limited to potassium, vitamin B6, manganese, thiamin, dietary fiber, and vitamin C. Yams generally have about half the glycemic index of potato products.

Name: Zucchini
Description: The zucchini or courgette is a summer squash which can reach nearly 3 feet in length, but is usually harvested immature at 6 to 10 inches. Like all squash, it has its ancestry in the Americas, however zucchini varieties were developed in northern Italy in the second half of the 19th century. When used for food, zucchini are usually picked at under 8 inches in length, when the seeds are still soft and immature. Zucchini has a delicate flavor and requires very little cooking, and is usually cooked with the skin in place.
